05475nam a22007695i 9780674269743DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20212021mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742697437 a10.4159/97806742697432doi  a(DE-B1597)590538  a(OCoLC)1291223895  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHX517.8aHM1131 7aHIS0370702bisacsh04a335.009172/42231 aFriedman, Jeremy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRipe for Revolution :bBuilding Socialism in the Third World /cJeremy Friedman. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction: Socialist Revolution as a Global Process -- t1. Asian Axis: The Indonesian Communist Party and the Struggle for Power in Sukarno’s Indonesia -- t2. Democratic Communism: Allende’s Chile and Peaceful Transition -- t3. Tanzanian Ujamaa : Building Socialism in a Communist World -- t4. Lenin without Marx: Communism Comes to Angola -- t5. Opiate of the Masses, or Stimulant? Socialism, Religion, and Revolution in Iran -- tConclusion: The Evolution of Socialism -- tArchive Sources -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA historical account of ideology in the Global South as the postwar laboratory of socialism, its legacy following the Cold War, and the continuing influence of socialist ideas worldwide. In the first decades after World War II, many newly independent Asian and African countries and established Latin American states pursued a socialist development model. Jeremy Friedman traces the socialist experiment over forty years through the experience of five countries: Indonesia, Chile, Tanzania, Angola, and Iran. These states sought paths to socialism without formal adherence to the Soviet bloc or the programs that Soviets, East Germans, Cubans, Chinese, and other outsiders tried to promote. Instead, they attempted to forge new models of socialist development through their own trial and error, together with the help of existing socialist countries, demonstrating the flexibility and adaptability of socialism. All five countries would become Cold War battlegrounds and regional models, as new policies in one shaped evolving conceptions of development in another. Lessons from the collapse of democracy in Indonesia were later applied in Chile, just as the challenge of political Islam in Indonesia informed the policies of the left in Iran. Efforts to build agrarian economies in West Africa influenced Tanzania’s approach to socialism, which in turn influenced the trajectory of the Angolan model. Ripe for Revolution shows socialism as more adaptable and pragmatic than often supposed. When we view it through the prism of a Stalinist orthodoxy, we miss its real effects and legacies, both good and bad. To understand how socialism succeeds and fails, and to grasp its evolution and potential horizons, we must do more than read manifestos. We must attend to history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aGlobalizationzDeveloping countries. 0aGlobalizationzSouthern Hemisphere. 0aSocialismzDeveloping countries. 0aSocialismzSouthern Hemisphere. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package: